Irene Githinji @gitshee The government has issued an alert over a looming drought in 14 counties. National Drought Management Authority (NDMA) report has revealed that 14 counties are in the normal drought phase while nine in the alert level. Authority said the trend is worsening in 13 counties namely Garissa, Isiolo, Kitui, Marsabit, Samburu, Tana River, Turkana, Wajir, Kilifi, Laikipia, Mandera, Nyeri (Kieni area) and West Pokot. However, the  government  assured that no child will miss classes due to drought, adding that it has put in place mitigation measures. It also said  it has averted a possible disruption of the academic calendar and other potential effects of the dry spell in the country. During an intergovernmental committee meeting that brought together six Cabinet secretaries at Harambee House, NDMA revealed that the current drought situation is less dire than last year’s. NDMA further said  work is in progress to strengthen the institutional and financing framework for drought management through the Ending Drought Emergencies (EDE) initiative. The meeting was attended by Interior Cabinet secretary Fred Matiang’i, counterparts Sicily Kariuki (Health), Najib Balala (Tourism), Amina Mohamed (Education), Mwangi Kiunjuri (Agriculture), Simon Chelugui (Water) and Eugene Wamalwa (Devolution). The CSs also said the government is mobilising resources for dietetic intervention programmes, health and outreach screening, and enhancement of medical supplies to the affected areas. They said emergency food supplies, water, and other non-food items will be provided to households, communities, and various institutions, including schools.